00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:10.710
KURT: Good morning everyone, and
welcome to our Talks at Google

00:00:10.710 --> 00:00:14.280
talk on electric vehicles,
electric and plug-in vehicles.

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:17.903
I'm pleased to welcome--
when I massacre your name,

00:00:17.903 --> 00:00:19.980
you'll correct me--
Gina Coplon-Newfield.

00:00:19.980 --> 00:00:23.540
She directs the Sierra Club's
environmental electric vehicles

00:00:23.540 --> 00:00:27.050
initiative which works on
the national and state levels

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:30.090
to advocate for electric
vehicle consumer initiatives

00:00:30.090 --> 00:00:33.313
and educates the media,
policy makers, and the public

00:00:33.313 --> 00:00:36.230
about the benefits
of plug-in vehicles.

00:00:36.230 --> 00:00:40.230
Brian Cali is the co-founder
of Ironwood Pharmaceuticals

00:00:40.230 --> 00:00:43.060
and has served as
the senior vice

00:00:43.060 --> 00:00:45.210
president of pre-clinical
research and development

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:47.850
since 2010.

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:50.710
Both these people are
members of the Sierra Club.

00:00:50.710 --> 00:00:54.100
Both of them own
plug-in vehicles.

00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:56.680
And I'd like you to say
good morning to them

00:00:56.680 --> 00:01:00.150
and we'll get going
with the talk.

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:06.105
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:06.105 --> 00:01:07.980
GINA COPLON-NEWFIELD:
Good morning everybody.

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:09.220
It's great to be here.

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:11.890
I use Google products
all the time.

00:01:11.890 --> 00:01:15.360
So thank you so much for
making my life so much easier.

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:17.920
And I happen to live
right here in Cambridge.

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:21.020
And as Kurt said, work
for the Sierra Club

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:24.310
which is headquartered in
California just like Google is.

00:01:24.310 --> 00:01:26.570
But I happen to work here.

00:01:26.570 --> 00:01:31.790
And also as Kurt said,
I'm a proud driver

00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:33.940
of a plug-in vehicle.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:36.780
So as you may know,
the Sierra Club

00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:39.580
is the oldest and largest
grassroots environmental

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:40.910
organization in the country.

00:01:40.910 --> 00:01:44.670
We were founded in the
late 1800s by John Muir.

00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:48.670
We have 2.4 million members
and supporters and chapters

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:50.020
in all 50 states.

00:01:50.020 --> 00:01:53.880
We work on a range of different
environmental issues including

00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:57.250
wilderness protection
and a range of campaigns

00:01:57.250 --> 00:02:01.060
that are confronting
climate change.

00:02:01.060 --> 00:02:05.200
Oil is one of the most
serious threats that we face.

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:08.259
Oil consumption
constitutes about 40%

00:02:08.259 --> 00:02:11.290
of US climate emissions.

00:02:11.290 --> 00:02:15.020
And as we all know,
climate emissions

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:17.600
are leading to some
pretty serious problems

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:22.980
in terms of increased storms,
droughts, fires, extreme

00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:25.340
weather, floods, et cetera.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:29.052
So I don't know about you,
but these kinds of things

00:02:29.052 --> 00:02:30.510
do keep me up a
little bit at night

00:02:30.510 --> 00:02:34.890
when I think about my children
and future grandchildren.

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:37.580
Climate change is a
clear and present danger

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:39.970
that we're facing.

00:02:39.970 --> 00:02:42.150
And so oil is a
big part of that.

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:45.580
We also know that we're spending
between a quarter and a half

00:02:45.580 --> 00:02:49.060
a billion dollars every
day to pay for foreign oil.

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:51.270
Often sending money
to countries that

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:55.180
are not necessarily
friendly to US policies.

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:58.610
And we also know that
there are examples

00:02:58.610 --> 00:03:02.060
like during the height of
the fighting in Afghanistan,

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:04.570
we heard from the
Secretary of the Navy

00:03:04.570 --> 00:03:08.300
that out of every
24 fuel convoys that

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:12.650
were being guarded
by US soldiers,

00:03:12.650 --> 00:03:16.600
one Marine or soldier was
getting injured or killed

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:19.000
for every 24 of
these fuel convoys.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:22.400
So that's a pretty heavy price
that we're paying for oil.

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:26.260
Fortunately, there are
alternatives to oil.

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:31.830
So we can get around, we can
move without having to use oil.

00:03:31.830 --> 00:03:34.480
So for those of you
who bike to work,

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:38.255
maybe not on a freezing
day like today, but maybe.

00:03:38.255 --> 00:03:40.130
Maybe there were some
brave people out there,

00:03:40.130 --> 00:03:42.120
or walk to work,
or took-- oh good,

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:44.980
a brave person in the audience--
or took public transit,

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:47.810
those are clearly the
cleanest ways to get around.

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:50.120
But we know that millions
of people in this country

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:52.350
and around the world
will continue to drive.

00:03:52.350 --> 00:03:57.010
So we need to find cleaner
ways to get around in our cars

00:03:57.010 --> 00:04:01.840
without having to rely on
any oil or as much oil.

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:05.270
So I love this graphic that
really makes it tangible.

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:09.690
You think about the BP
Gulf oil disaster that

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:13.750
happened a few years ago and
you think about all the oil

00:04:13.750 --> 00:04:15.430
that went into the
Gulf of Mexico.

00:04:15.430 --> 00:04:19.600
And if we had a million
electric vehicles on the road,

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:23.860
that would be saving
the same amount of oil.

00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:25.790
So how many people
in the audience

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:28.000
saw the State of the
Union Address last night?

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.500
Excellent, some fellow
policy nerds like me

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:33.210
who love that sort of thing.

00:04:33.210 --> 00:04:37.630
So this is a quote from
President Obama's State

00:04:37.630 --> 00:04:39.630
of the Union Address
four years ago

00:04:39.630 --> 00:04:42.550
when he said, "we can
break our dependence on oil

00:04:42.550 --> 00:04:44.290
and become the first
country to have

00:04:44.290 --> 00:04:48.540
one million electric vehicles
on the road in 2015,"

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:52.120
Now it is 2015.

00:04:52.120 --> 00:04:54.300
It is four years later now.

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:58.050
Will we have one million
electric vehicles on US roads

00:04:58.050 --> 00:04:59.810
by the end of this year?

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:00.310
No.

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:02.090
We will not, unfortunately.

00:05:02.090 --> 00:05:04.390
So we will not meet this goal.

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:09.010
But we will have
somewhere around 400,000

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:11.580
electric vehicles on the
road by the end of the year.

00:05:11.580 --> 00:05:15.560
And we think we'll hit that
one million mark around 2018.

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:20.180
So EVs, or electric vehicles,
are gaining market share faster

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:22.780
than hybrids gained market
share when they first

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:24.480
hit the market
about 15 years ago.

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:25.940
So that's encouraging.

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:27.880
The Obama administration
has definitely

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:30.280
invested in electric vehicles
through the Department

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:34.210
of Energy's research, through
grants and programs that

00:05:34.210 --> 00:05:38.800
are supporting public charging
stations around the country.

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:40.430
And through the
federal tax credit.

00:05:40.430 --> 00:05:43.630
If you bought an
electric vehicle,

00:05:43.630 --> 00:05:48.200
you would get somewhere
between $2,500 and $7,500

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:51.520
in a federal tax break,
which is certainly

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:55.950
nothing to sneeze at in
terms of an incentive.

00:05:55.950 --> 00:05:58.900
So we're very fortunate to
have an administration that's

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:03.480
really supportive of this issue.

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:05.310
So now is an exciting time.

00:06:05.310 --> 00:06:07.750
Four years ago when President
Obama give that speech,

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:10.550
there were almost no electric
vehicles on the road.

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:12.880
Now there are more
than a quarter million

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:16.310
and there are about 20
models that are available.

00:06:16.310 --> 00:06:18.890
Not all of these models are
available in Massachusetts

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:20.250
but a lot of them are.

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:25.470
So there's the BMW i3,
there's the plug-in Prius,

00:06:25.470 --> 00:06:30.770
there is the Nissan LEAF, the
Chevy Volt, the Tesla Model S.

00:06:30.770 --> 00:06:34.010
All the different Ford models,
the Ford Fusion, the Ford

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:35.080
C-Max.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:37.170
So there are a lot of
great options out there.

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:40.710
Raise your hand if you've driven
in an electric vehicle before?

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:41.470
OK.

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:42.290
Fantastic.

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:44.930
Raise your hand if you actually
own one or drive one yourself.

00:06:44.930 --> 00:06:45.470
Great.

00:06:45.470 --> 00:06:45.970
Oh good.

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:47.110
A couple examples.

00:06:47.110 --> 00:06:48.610
So if you've been
in one before, you

00:06:48.610 --> 00:06:50.800
know these are really fun cars.

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:53.230
They're quiet,
they're fast, they're

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:55.740
very technologically advanced.

00:06:55.740 --> 00:06:58.712
They are easier and
cheaper to maintain

00:06:58.712 --> 00:07:00.420
than a conventional
vehicle because there

00:07:00.420 --> 00:07:03.900
are fewer moving parts involved.

00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:06.140
And they're just
really fun to drive.

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:08.840
We talk in the electric
vehicles world a lot

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:13.070
about getting butts in
seats because so many people

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:15.720
out there just don't realize
that they're available

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:19.980
or they think they're
this futuristic thing that

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:22.882
aren't accessible to
real normal people.

00:07:22.882 --> 00:07:24.340
But once you get
inside one and you

00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:28.140
drive it or you ride in one you
know that this is, it's here.

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:30.949
It's available now and
it's a lot of fun to drive.

00:07:30.949 --> 00:07:33.490
They don't necessarily work for
everybody's lifestyle, right?

00:07:33.490 --> 00:07:35.780
So if you live in an
apartment building where

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:38.470
you don't have any
access to parking,

00:07:38.470 --> 00:07:43.600
or a driveway, or garage where
you could plug the car in,

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:45.970
it's going to be challenging
to have an electric car.

00:07:45.970 --> 00:07:50.540
Now if you have a place to plug
it in at work or around town

00:07:50.540 --> 00:07:52.580
and that's convenient
for you, great.

00:07:52.580 --> 00:07:54.030
That could work out.

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:56.250
But for some people, they're
just not going to work.

00:07:56.250 --> 00:08:00.100
But the Union of Concerned
Scientists and consumer's union

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:03.930
did a survey a year or so ago
and they found that almost half

00:08:03.930 --> 00:08:07.100
of Americans actually could
make an electric vehicle

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:08.990
work for their lifestyle.

00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:12.100
So more people than
one might think

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:16.600
could be ready for an electric
car as their next car.

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:20.280
So I'll list just a few
examples of some of the things

00:08:20.280 --> 00:08:25.490
that Sierra Club is doing to
advance electric vehicles.

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:27.080
As I said, we're
working on this issue

00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:32.120
because we see oil and climate
change as really important

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:35.799
issues to address and electric
vehicles as one key way

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:37.710
to address those problems.

00:08:37.710 --> 00:08:39.220
So we're doing a few things.

00:08:39.220 --> 00:08:40.710
So one is public education.

00:08:40.710 --> 00:08:42.929
So we have public events.

00:08:42.929 --> 00:08:46.050
We've been having National
Drive Electric Week.

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:49.410
These are opportunities to
have electric vehicle promotion

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:50.660
events all around the country.

00:08:50.660 --> 00:08:53.080
So last year we had
National Drive Electric Week

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:57.580
in September where we had EV
promotion events in 150 cities

00:08:57.580 --> 00:08:58.400
around the country.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:02.920
We got 90,000 or so people to
attend, about 200 media hits.

00:09:02.920 --> 00:09:05.490
So it was just a really
good way to educate

00:09:05.490 --> 00:09:08.350
the masses, or at least
some segment of the masses,

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:10.790
about electric cars.

00:09:10.790 --> 00:09:13.240
We do blogging and
media outreach.

00:09:13.240 --> 00:09:14.600
We have a website.

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:16.460
We also do policy advocacy.

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:19.810
So I mentioned the federal
tax credit, which is helpful.

00:09:19.810 --> 00:09:23.490
But it's also helpful to
have states incentives.

00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:26.120
So for example,
state rebates that

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:28.670
are on top of the
federal tax credit.

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:30.330
And I'll mention the
Massachusetts one

00:09:30.330 --> 00:09:32.520
in a few minutes.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:33.760
Carpooling access.

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:36.100
If you live in
California, you know

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:38.760
that those carpooling
stickers are like gold.

00:09:38.760 --> 00:09:42.060
There is literally a black
market for these stickers

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:44.060
because people are so
desperate to get out

00:09:44.060 --> 00:09:47.030
of traffic and the
hours and hours

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:48.330
that they spend in traffic.

00:09:48.330 --> 00:09:51.320
So if you can have that carpool
lane sticker, even if you're

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:55.100
the only one driving as an
electric-vehicle driver,

00:09:55.100 --> 00:09:56.130
that's like gold.

00:09:56.130 --> 00:09:58.210
So having those kinds
of carpool-lane access

00:09:58.210 --> 00:10:01.920
in other states, that is
really helpful as well.

00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:06.860
A waiver on parking registration
or emissions tests, these kinds

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:09.550
of small things we found
can make a difference.

00:10:09.550 --> 00:10:12.830
So getting more of them
in place in more states,

00:10:12.830 --> 00:10:14.990
like Massachusetts,
is definitely

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:17.640
going to help accelerate the
electric vehicles market.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:22.910
In fact, who knows the number
one state right now per capita

00:10:22.910 --> 00:10:25.490
for electric vehicle sales?

00:10:25.490 --> 00:10:26.490
So I'll give you a hint.

00:10:26.490 --> 00:10:29.740
It is not California and
it is not Massachusetts.

00:10:29.740 --> 00:10:31.260
It is Georgia.

00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:33.940
And the reason it is
Georgia is because there

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:38.030
is a really generous
credit for driving

00:10:38.030 --> 00:10:40.060
an electric car in Georgia.

00:10:40.060 --> 00:10:43.030
There's a significant discount
for driving an electric car

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:46.540
there because there's
this incentive in place.

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:49.404
And so these incentives
definitely make a difference.

00:10:49.404 --> 00:10:50.820
So just to give
you a little sense

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:54.150
of the scale of how fast
we need to ramp up demand,

00:10:54.150 --> 00:10:55.970
we hired a consulting
firm to help

00:10:55.970 --> 00:10:58.940
us evaluate how we can
make the biggest impact

00:10:58.940 --> 00:11:02.100
and how fast we need to
accelerate this market.

00:11:02.100 --> 00:11:04.840
And what they
helped us understand

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:08.420
is that by the year
2025, we're expecting

00:11:08.420 --> 00:11:10.830
to have about four million
electric cars on the road.

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:15.320
Now think about the fact that
we have about 250 million cars

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:19.390
registered in this country,
cars and light trucks.

00:11:19.390 --> 00:11:23.430
So that's still a very small
sliver of the vehicle market.

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:26.970
Now with an aggressive
campaign that's successful,

00:11:26.970 --> 00:11:29.550
we think we can bump that
up to somewhere between five

00:11:29.550 --> 00:11:32.315
and seven million
electric vehicles by 2025.

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:38.970
Where we think we need to be by
2025 to meet our climate goals

00:11:38.970 --> 00:11:42.940
is more like 10 million
EVs on the road by 2025.

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:45.370
So we really need to
redouble our efforts

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:49.540
and find other stakeholders,
other NGOs, other companies,

00:11:49.540 --> 00:11:51.930
government agencies,
that we can partner with

00:11:51.930 --> 00:11:56.320
to really focus on
accelerating this market.

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:59.200
So I won't get too much into the
weeds in terms of the policies

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:00.722
that we're promoting.

00:12:00.722 --> 00:12:03.180
We can get back to that during
the Q&amp;A session if folks are

00:12:03.180 --> 00:12:06.880
interested in , but these are
some of the key strategies that

00:12:06.880 --> 00:12:08.050
we think are important.

00:12:08.050 --> 00:12:09.850
Public awareness,
which I mentioned.

00:12:09.850 --> 00:12:12.100
The consumer incentives.

00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:13.610
Workplace charging.

00:12:13.610 --> 00:12:15.690
The Department of
Energy has a program

00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:18.700
called the EV Everywhere
Workplace Charging

00:12:18.700 --> 00:12:21.590
Challenge, which
is a mouth full.

00:12:21.590 --> 00:12:23.560
And this is a program
that's working

00:12:23.560 --> 00:12:27.540
to recruit about 500 major
businesses around the US

00:12:27.540 --> 00:12:30.760
to join the program,
install charging stations

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:34.270
at workplaces, and get
more employees excited

00:12:34.270 --> 00:12:35.900
about electric cars.

00:12:35.900 --> 00:12:39.810
They did a survey and
found that if somebody

00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:42.950
has access to electric
vehicle charging at work,

00:12:42.950 --> 00:12:46.910
they are 20 times more likely
to drive an electric car then

00:12:46.910 --> 00:12:47.880
the average person.

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:50.840
So clearly these workplace
charging programs

00:12:50.840 --> 00:12:51.640
make a difference.

00:12:51.640 --> 00:12:55.590
Google is a member of
this workplace charging

00:12:55.590 --> 00:12:57.570
program, which is fantastic.

00:12:57.570 --> 00:12:59.880
My understanding
is that there are

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:04.260
lots of EV chargers in
California at Google offices.

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:06.180
I don't think, correct
me if I'm wrong,

00:13:06.180 --> 00:13:08.260
I don't think
Google has installed

00:13:08.260 --> 00:13:10.160
any here in Cambridge.

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:12.590
I know there are few
charging stations around here

00:13:12.590 --> 00:13:16.034
but not necessarily
installed by Google.

00:13:16.034 --> 00:13:17.450
Somebody in the
audience is saying

00:13:17.450 --> 00:13:21.280
zero which means that there
is a need for more charging

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:23.130
stations in the area.

00:13:23.130 --> 00:13:25.880
So if anyone is actually
interested in working

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:29.100
with Google to get more charging
stations installed around here,

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:31.040
I would be happy
to partner with you

00:13:31.040 --> 00:13:34.450
to connect with the right folks
in your California offices

00:13:34.450 --> 00:13:37.669
and see if we can
make that happen.

00:13:37.669 --> 00:13:38.960
Public charging infrastructure.

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:43.240
Most people will charge at home
overnight, which is actually

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:44.660
good for the grid too, right?

00:13:44.660 --> 00:13:49.070
Because most people are using
electricity when they're awake.

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:51.500
And so if we can
be shifting some

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:53.982
of the load, the electricity
load, to the night,

00:13:53.982 --> 00:13:56.440
that actually makes everything
a little bit more efficient.

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:57.680
So that's a good thing.

00:13:57.680 --> 00:14:01.180
But it is nice to have access to
public charging infrastructure.

00:14:01.180 --> 00:14:05.100
So if you're taking
a longer trip

00:14:05.100 --> 00:14:08.040
and you want access to charging
infrastructure along the way

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:08.692
that's helpful.

00:14:08.692 --> 00:14:10.400
If you're going to be
stopping at a place

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:13.600
to shop for an hour or
so and want to top off,

00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:16.140
it's nice to be able to
have a charging station.

00:14:16.140 --> 00:14:18.510
So places like
Ikea are installing

00:14:18.510 --> 00:14:20.560
charging stations,
which is great.

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:21.770
And then utility programs.

00:14:21.770 --> 00:14:25.580
If you think about the
fact that right now,

00:14:25.580 --> 00:14:28.570
the vast majority
of the market share

00:14:28.570 --> 00:14:31.340
for the fuel for
our vehicles goes

00:14:31.340 --> 00:14:35.240
to companies like
Exxon Mobil and Shell,

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:38.480
and if we can shift some
of that market share

00:14:38.480 --> 00:14:42.800
to domestic utility
companies, that

00:14:42.800 --> 00:14:45.360
could be a really great
opportunity for these utility

00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:47.730
companies to take some
of that market share.

00:14:47.730 --> 00:14:50.480
And some utility companies are
starting to figure that out,

00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:52.960
that this is a great
opportunity for them.

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:55.499
But we need more of
them to do the math

00:14:55.499 --> 00:14:57.040
and figure it out
and also figure out

00:14:57.040 --> 00:14:59.780
how to incentivize electric
vehicles through things

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:05.480
like cheaper electricity rates
for electric-vehicle drivers

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:08.380
or cheaper nighttime rates,
which is again, the time when

00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:11.680
most people will charge
their electric vehicles.

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:15.930
So I encourage everybody to
check out our website which is

00:15:15.930 --> 00:15:21.010
www.sierraclub.org/evguide.

00:15:21.010 --> 00:15:23.660
If you go there, you
can click on just

00:15:23.660 --> 00:15:26.120
about any electric vehicle
which is on the market.

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:27.880
We're actually
working to update it.

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:30.380
There are few new models that
we haven't gotten up there yet

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:31.660
but we're working on it.

00:15:31.660 --> 00:15:33.380
You click on the
car, you find out

00:15:33.380 --> 00:15:35.060
some information about the car.

00:15:35.060 --> 00:15:37.100
And then it gets interactive.

00:15:37.100 --> 00:15:40.010
You put in your zip
code and it tells you

00:15:40.010 --> 00:15:42.170
things like how
much money you're

00:15:42.170 --> 00:15:46.290
saving in gasoline
versus electricity

00:15:46.290 --> 00:15:48.120
costs for fueling your vehicle.

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:49.980
How much gasoline
you're avoiding.

00:15:49.980 --> 00:15:53.290
How much oil you're not
using and consuming.

00:15:53.290 --> 00:15:55.810
How much you're saving
in emissions, right?

00:15:55.810 --> 00:15:58.100
So we've done the
math and figured out

00:15:58.100 --> 00:16:00.800
that even with the
emissions associated

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:03.880
with the electricity used
to charge your vehicle,

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:05.430
your electric vehicle
is still going

00:16:05.430 --> 00:16:09.190
to be much cleaner than
a conventional vehicle.

00:16:09.190 --> 00:16:10.620
You've probably
heard people say,

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:12.600
oh electric cars
aren't so clean.

00:16:12.600 --> 00:16:14.720
They're just coal
cars because we're

00:16:14.720 --> 00:16:16.630
using fossil fuels
to charge them.

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:19.080
Raise your hand if you've
heard people say that.

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:21.020
Yeah, pretty much
everybody has heard that.

00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:23.720
I hear it every day from
Sierra Club supporters

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:26.590
who are understandably
concerned about coal,

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:29.339
and natural gas,
and fossil fuels.

00:16:29.339 --> 00:16:29.880
That's great.

00:16:29.880 --> 00:16:33.940
We want people concerned about
these issues but rest assured,

00:16:33.940 --> 00:16:35.850
we've done the math
and figured out

00:16:35.850 --> 00:16:38.440
that even factoring
in the emissions

00:16:38.440 --> 00:16:41.080
associated with charging
electric vehicles,

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:43.470
they are still
significantly cleaner

00:16:43.470 --> 00:16:44.740
than conventional vehicles.

00:16:44.740 --> 00:16:46.990
And in a region
like New England,

00:16:46.990 --> 00:16:51.540
that is especially true because
our reliance on the dirtiest

00:16:51.540 --> 00:16:55.020
form of electricity, coal,
is actually pretty low

00:16:55.020 --> 00:16:57.820
compared to other
parts of the country.

00:16:57.820 --> 00:17:02.550
So in Massachusetts, if you are
charging your electric vehicle,

00:17:02.550 --> 00:17:04.730
let's say it's a fully
electric vehicle.

00:17:04.730 --> 00:17:07.800
It's going to be about
60 to 70% cleaner

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:10.650
in terms of carbon emissions
than a conventional vehicle.

00:17:10.650 --> 00:17:14.119
The average conventional vehicle
that you would buy today.

00:17:14.119 --> 00:17:17.310
So that's pretty significant
and it's pretty interesting.

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:18.760
So if you go to
this website, you

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:20.609
can find out
information like that.

00:17:20.609 --> 00:17:22.040
We also have a quiz.

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:24.560
It's a really short
online quiz that

00:17:24.560 --> 00:17:27.569
helps you figure out which
EV might be best for you

00:17:27.569 --> 00:17:29.670
based on a variety of factors.

00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:32.401
So check out the website.

00:17:32.401 --> 00:17:33.900
And now let me tell
you a little bit

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:37.530
about some interesting
opportunities in Massachusetts.

00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:40.580
So I serve on the
Governor's EV Task Force

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:43.640
in Massachusetts
which has started

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:47.840
to put in place some exciting
programs and incentives that

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:51.310
make electric vehicles more
appealing in Massachusetts.

00:17:51.310 --> 00:17:54.460
And the most exciting
part of that is a rebate.

00:17:54.460 --> 00:17:58.990
So that means if you lease or
purchase an electric vehicle

00:17:58.990 --> 00:18:01.220
in Massachusetts,
you literally get

00:18:01.220 --> 00:18:06.890
a check in the mail for anywhere
between $1,500 to $2,500,

00:18:06.890 --> 00:18:10.210
depending on the size of
the battery of your vehicle.

00:18:10.210 --> 00:18:12.840
So it's a great opportunity.

00:18:12.840 --> 00:18:16.290
Our funding source
for that program,

00:18:16.290 --> 00:18:17.854
right now it's a
pilot program, it

00:18:17.854 --> 00:18:20.020
looks like it may run out
in the next couple months.

00:18:20.020 --> 00:18:22.270
So I would say if you're
thinking of buying or leasing

00:18:22.270 --> 00:18:25.754
a car in the next few months and
you're thinking about electric,

00:18:25.754 --> 00:18:28.170
now is a great time to do it
before that funding runs out.

00:18:28.170 --> 00:18:31.130
We're going to be working to
get that funding source renewed

00:18:31.130 --> 00:18:32.800
but there may be a gap period.

00:18:32.800 --> 00:18:37.500
So I'd encourage you to
move faster than slower.

00:18:37.500 --> 00:18:40.160
And here is the website where
you can find out information

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:42.360
about this program
here in Massachusetts.

00:18:42.360 --> 00:18:43.620
So it's mor-ev.org.

