00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:35.109
can do Q and A after that.

00:19:35.109 --> 00:19:37.150
BRIAN CALI: So thanks very
much and good morning.

00:19:37.150 --> 00:19:41.014
I own an EV because I met
Gina actually at another event

00:19:41.014 --> 00:19:41.680
that we were at.

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:44.092
And it happened to be
at that perfect time

00:19:44.092 --> 00:19:45.800
when I was considering
what we were going

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:48.204
to do with the Prius that
was at the end of its life

00:19:48.204 --> 00:19:49.870
and the fact that we
needed another car.

00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:52.610
So the timing was
absolutely perfect.

00:19:52.610 --> 00:19:55.740
And I came here
today because I think

00:19:55.740 --> 00:19:57.350
that early adopters
of technology

00:19:57.350 --> 00:19:58.309
play an important role.

00:19:58.309 --> 00:20:00.016
And there are some of
you who are already

00:20:00.016 --> 00:20:02.170
driving electric vehicles,
which is awesome.

00:20:02.170 --> 00:20:03.190
And I'm assuming
that the rest of you

00:20:03.190 --> 00:20:05.460
are here because you're at
least somewhat interested.

00:20:05.460 --> 00:20:07.990
And so I think it's an
opportunity for those of us

00:20:07.990 --> 00:20:11.340
who own to share our
experiences and answer questions

00:20:11.340 --> 00:20:13.200
that people may have
so that there might

00:20:13.200 --> 00:20:15.080
be some other folks
who decide to adopt.

00:20:15.080 --> 00:20:17.371
So actually, I don't have a
lot of prepared statements.

00:20:17.371 --> 00:20:18.850
I think really
ultimately the role

00:20:18.850 --> 00:20:21.016
is going to be to answer
questions that people have.

00:20:21.016 --> 00:20:24.330
But just briefly I'll tell you
about my experience so far.

00:20:24.330 --> 00:20:27.900
So we bought our Nissan
Leaf in June of this year.

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:30.980
I did a little bit of analytics
before I came here today

00:20:30.980 --> 00:20:32.932
just to kind of take a
look at average energy

00:20:32.932 --> 00:20:34.890
consumption and other
things that we were doing

00:20:34.890 --> 00:20:38.510
to kind of think about what
the cost impact for us has been

00:20:38.510 --> 00:20:41.710
and how that matched up to what
I would expect to have seen.

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:45.522
So before I go into that,
what I will tell you is we've

00:20:45.522 --> 00:20:46.980
been really delighted
with the car.

00:20:46.980 --> 00:20:49.760
The car gets most of it's
use for my wife actually

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:52.580
who commutes up to Salem
everyday from Arlington, MA.

00:20:52.580 --> 00:20:54.650
So she drives up
there every day.

00:20:54.650 --> 00:20:57.290
It's about a 29-mile
one-way trip.

00:20:57.290 --> 00:20:58.650
She comes back down.

00:20:58.650 --> 00:21:01.480
So it's 58-mile round
trip and there's still

00:21:01.480 --> 00:21:03.822
miles left on the charge
to get around and run

00:21:03.822 --> 00:21:05.030
some other errands every day.

00:21:05.030 --> 00:21:07.980
So we have yet to what's called,
"turtling the car," which

00:21:07.980 --> 00:21:09.680
is totally running
out of energy and be

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:10.930
stuck on the side of the road.

00:21:10.930 --> 00:21:12.056
We haven't turtled once.

00:21:12.056 --> 00:21:13.430
You definitely,
as an experience,

00:21:13.430 --> 00:21:15.805
you always start out thinking,
how much charge do I have?

00:21:15.805 --> 00:21:17.770
And I want to make sure
that I don't use it up.

00:21:17.770 --> 00:21:20.404
So you're paying a
little more attention

00:21:20.404 --> 00:21:23.070
than you would if you're driving
a gas-powered vehicle where you

00:21:23.070 --> 00:21:25.028
can always find a gas
station and get some gas.

00:21:25.028 --> 00:21:27.290
So that's definitely
there but you

00:21:27.290 --> 00:21:29.250
get used to it very quickly.

00:21:29.250 --> 00:21:31.210
I would say that the
surprise that I had is I'm

00:21:31.210 --> 00:21:33.180
not really a car
person in the sense

00:21:33.180 --> 00:21:35.387
that I'm not all that
interested in buying

00:21:35.387 --> 00:21:36.470
high-performance vehicles.

00:21:36.470 --> 00:21:39.145
I've never really had, I
drove that Prius I told you

00:21:39.145 --> 00:21:42.191
and before that, we drove the
Honda Civics my entire driving

00:21:42.191 --> 00:21:42.690
career.

00:21:42.690 --> 00:21:46.002
And I will tell you, this Leaf
is really, really fun to drive.

00:21:46.002 --> 00:21:48.210
Even as somebody who doesn't
care about those things.

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:51.810
It's incredibly zippy.

00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:54.045
In traffic it's really
fun to be able to weave

00:21:54.045 --> 00:21:54.920
in and out of things.

00:21:54.920 --> 00:21:57.437
It's small, high performance,
that low center of gravity

00:21:57.437 --> 00:21:59.270
makes you feel like
when you're going around

00:21:59.270 --> 00:22:00.882
turns that it really just turns.

00:22:00.882 --> 00:22:02.340
It takes those
turns really nicely.

00:22:02.340 --> 00:22:03.570
So it's actually been
really fun to drive.

00:22:03.570 --> 00:22:05.153
And we have four
drivers in our house.

00:22:05.153 --> 00:22:07.220
And we all fight for the
Leaf, basically whenever

00:22:07.220 --> 00:22:08.950
somebody wants to
go on an errand.

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:10.530
So it's a really
fun car to drive.

00:22:10.530 --> 00:22:12.920
We looked at some other
ones too at the time.

00:22:12.920 --> 00:22:15.890
And for us, again,
family of five,

00:22:15.890 --> 00:22:18.300
it really does, and I put
that in my bio that was here,

00:22:18.300 --> 00:22:20.545
we can fit our entire
family and our dog who

00:22:20.545 --> 00:22:23.200
is a 40-pound mutt
down in the bay

00:22:23.200 --> 00:22:25.200
and still feel like,
we're packed in there,

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:26.650
but it's not ridiculous.

00:22:26.650 --> 00:22:28.470
We've even done
some trips that way.

00:22:28.470 --> 00:22:30.590
So it's a great, I
would say for us,

00:22:30.590 --> 00:22:33.220
second car, because we
do take longer trips

00:22:33.220 --> 00:22:35.610
as a family and
that obviously where

00:22:35.610 --> 00:22:37.361
we get an 80-mile range
in the summertime.

00:22:37.361 --> 00:22:39.110
That's the other thing
I wanted to mention

00:22:39.110 --> 00:22:41.170
is as we've headed into
the winter and it's cold,

00:22:41.170 --> 00:22:43.340
both the performance of
the battery goes down

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:47.300
and you're using
heat which generates

00:22:47.300 --> 00:22:49.260
more draw on the system.

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:52.050
And so we're averaging
around more like 60

00:22:52.050 --> 00:22:54.735
to 65 miles on the charge
in the winter time.

00:22:54.735 --> 00:22:58.590
That's been-- for us in
terms of impact on the house,

00:22:58.590 --> 00:23:03.431
in terms of energy usage, it
adds about 250 kilowatt hours

00:23:03.431 --> 00:23:03.930
per month.

00:23:03.930 --> 00:23:05.305
You probably know
how much energy

00:23:05.305 --> 00:23:06.960
you're using at your own home.

00:23:06.960 --> 00:23:09.822
We've added on average 250
kilowatt hours on top of that.

00:23:09.822 --> 00:23:11.280
Which is interesting
because I also

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:13.260
know the mileage
that we're getting

00:23:13.260 --> 00:23:17.099
and I have now figured
out that basically

00:23:17.099 --> 00:23:19.140
about 80% of the energy
that we're using to power

00:23:19.140 --> 00:23:22.250
our car is coming from what I'm
doing by plugging in our house.

00:23:22.250 --> 00:23:24.915
And we're getting about 20%
out at charging stations

00:23:24.915 --> 00:23:27.030
that are out and around,
none of which we pay for.

00:23:27.030 --> 00:23:30.010
So I know that the system
pays for it ultimately

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:33.300
but the charging stations
at work or in communities

00:23:33.300 --> 00:23:35.550
that we're parking at that
are essentially free to us,

00:23:35.550 --> 00:23:37.450
they're all
charge-point systems.

00:23:37.450 --> 00:23:40.090
I've yet to be charged for
any one of my charging events.

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:43.280
So I'm getting about 20% of
that basically out of pocket.

00:23:43.280 --> 00:23:45.920
So I think the other
thing I would say

00:23:45.920 --> 00:23:48.590
is we, in contrast
to Gina, are not

00:23:48.590 --> 00:23:50.160
able to put solar on our roof.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:52.035
That would've been a
really nice thing for us

00:23:52.035 --> 00:23:54.950
to do to get the notion that
we would be completely powering

00:23:54.950 --> 00:23:56.940
our car with solar energy.

00:23:56.940 --> 00:23:58.260
There are options.

00:23:58.260 --> 00:24:00.026
And the one that I
did for a little while

00:24:00.026 --> 00:24:01.650
is the NSTAR Green,
where you basically

00:24:01.650 --> 00:24:04.880
pay a premium on top of
your regular electric bill.

00:24:04.880 --> 00:24:06.422
Maybe some of you
are doing that too.

00:24:06.422 --> 00:24:08.130
Basically what you're
doing at that point

00:24:08.130 --> 00:24:10.400
is it's not as if you're
buying green energy directly,

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:13.560
you're subsidizing or
creating a market for energy

00:24:13.560 --> 00:24:16.232
that is generated in
more renewable ways.

00:24:16.232 --> 00:24:18.440
There's another program that
we're actually using now

00:24:18.440 --> 00:24:21.310
through Mass Energy that is
less expensive than NSTAR

00:24:21.310 --> 00:24:22.450
Green for us.

00:24:22.450 --> 00:24:24.300
And so basically,
we're paying $0.04 more

00:24:24.300 --> 00:24:28.050
per kilowatt hour but all
of that is going directly

00:24:28.050 --> 00:24:31.059
to pay for wind-generated
energy in this particular case.

00:24:31.059 --> 00:24:32.850
